# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: krylov-subspace-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] In numerical linear algebra, the **Arnoldi iteration** is an eigenvalue algorithm and an important example of an iterative method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Arnoldi finds an approximation to the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of general (possibly non-Hermitian) matrices by constructing an orthonormal basis of the Krylov subspace, which makes it particularly useful when dealing with large sparse matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi method belongs to a class of linear algebra algorithms that give a partial result after a small number of iterations, in contrast to so-called *direct methods* which must complete to give any useful results (see for example, Householder transformation).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The partial result in this case being the first few vectors of the basis the algorithm is building.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] When applied to Hermitian matrices it reduces to the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi iteration was invented by W.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] An intuitive method for finding the largest (in absolute value) eigenvalue of a given *m* × *m* matrix A is the power iteration: starting with an arbitrary initial vector *b*, calculate *Ab*, *A*2*b*, *A*3*b*, ... normalizing the result after every application of the matrix *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This sequence converges to the eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value, $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] However, much potentially useful computation is wasted by using only the final result, $A^{n-1}b$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The columns of this matrix are not in general orthogonal, but we can extract an orthogonal basis, via a method such as Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The resulting set of vectors is thus an orthogonal basis of the *Krylov subspace*, ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] We may expect the vectors of this basis to span good approximations of the eigenvectors corresponding to the n largest eigenvalues, for the same reason that $A^{n-1}b$ approximates the dominant eigenvector.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The Arnoldi iteration uses the modified Gram–Schmidt process to produce a sequence of orthonormal vectors, *q*1, *q*2, *q*3, ..., called the *Arnoldi vectors*, such that for every *n*, the vectors *q*1, ..., *q**n* span the Krylov subspace ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The *j*-loop projects out the component of $q_{k}$ in the directions of $q_{1},\dots ,q_{k-1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This ensures the orthogonality of all the generated vectors.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The algorithm breaks down when *q**k* is the zero vector.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This happens when the minimal polynomial of *A* is of degree *k*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] In most applications of the Arnoldi iteration, including the eigenvalue algorithm below and GMRES, the algorithm has converged at this point.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Every step of the *k*-loop takes one matrix-vector product and approximately 4*mk* floating point operations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The orthogonalization method has to be specifically chosen such that the lower Arnoldi/Krylov components are removed from higher Krylov vectors.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The matrix *H**n* can be viewed as *A* in the subspace ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ with the Arnoldi vectors as an orthogonal basis; *A* is orthogonally projected onto ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The matrix *H**n* can be characterized by the following optimality condition.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The characteristic polynomial of *H**n* minimizes ||*p*(*A*)*q*1||2 among all monic polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This optimality problem has a unique solution if and only if the Arnoldi iteration does not break down.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] is an (*n*+1)-by-*n* matrix formed by adding an extra row to *H**n*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The idea of the Arnoldi iteration as an eigenvalue algorithm is to compute the eigenvalues in the Krylov subspace.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] The eigenvalues of *H**n* are called the *Ritz eigenvalues*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Since *H**n* is a Hessenberg matrix of modest size, its eigenvalues can be computed efficiently, for instance with the QR algorithm, or somewhat related, Francis' algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Also Francis' algorithm itself can be considered to be related to power iterations, operating on nested Krylov subspace.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] In fact, the most basic form of Francis' algorithm appears to be to choose *b* to be equal to *Ae*1, and extending *n* to the full dimension of *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Improved versions include one or more shifts, and higher powers of *A* may be applied in a single steps.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This is an example of the Rayleigh-Ritz method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] It is often observed in practice that some of the Ritz eigenvalues converge to eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Since *H**n* is *n*-by-*n*, it has at most *n* eigenvalues, and not all eigenvalues of *A* can be approximated.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Typically, the Ritz eigenvalues converge to the largest eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] To get the smallest eigenvalues of *A*, the inverse (operation) of *A* should be used instead.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This can be related to the characterization of *H**n* as the matrix whose characteristic polynomial minimizes ||*p*(*A*)*q*1|| in the following way.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] A good way to get *p*(*A*) small is to choose the polynomial *p* such that *p*(*x*) is small whenever *x* is an eigenvalue of *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Hence, the zeros of *p* (and thus the Ritz eigenvalues) will be close to the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] However, the details are not fully understood yet.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] This is in contrast to the case where *A* is Hermitian.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] In that situation, the Arnoldi iteration becomes the Lanczos iteration, for which the theory is more complete.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Due to practical storage consideration, common implementations of Arnoldi methods typically restart after a fixed number of iterations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] One approach is the Implicitly Restarted Arnoldi Method (IRAM) by Lehoucq and Sorensen, which was popularized in the free and open source software package ARPACK.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Another approach is the Krylov-Schur Algorithm by G.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/arnoldi-iteration] Stewart, which is more stable and simpler to implement than IRAM.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In numerical linear algebra, the **biconjugate gradient stabilized method**, often abbreviated as **BiCGSTAB**, is an iterative method developed by H.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] A. van der Vorst for the numerical solution of nonsymmetric linear systems.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] It is a variant of the biconjugate gradient method (BiCG) and has faster and smoother convergence than the original BiCG as well as other variants such as the conjugate gradient squared method (CGS).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] Unlike the original BiCG method, it doesn't require multiplication by the transpose of the system matrix.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In some cases, choosing the vector ***r̂***0 randomly improves numerical stability.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] Preconditioners are usually used to accelerate convergence of iterative methods.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In other words, both left- and right-preconditioning are possible with this formulation.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] It is unnecessary to explicitly keep track of the residuals and search directions of BiCG.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In other words, the BiCG iterations can be performed implicitly.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] Now it remains to determine the BiCG constants *αi* and *βi* and choose a suitable *ωi*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] Since BiCGSTAB does not explicitly keep track of ***r̂****i* or ***r****i*, *ρi* is not immediately computable from this formula.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] A simple formula for *αi* can be similarly derived.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] Similarly to the case above, only the highest-order terms of *P**i*−1(***A***T) and *T**i*−1(***A***T) matter in the dot products thanks to biorthogonality and biconjugacy.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] BiCGSTAB can be viewed as a combination of BiCG and GMRES where each BiCG step is followed by a GMRES(1) (i.e., GMRES restarted at each step) step to repair the irregular convergence behavior of CGS, as an improvement of which BiCGSTAB was developed.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] However, due to the use of degree-one minimum residual polynomials, such repair may not be effective if the matrix ***A*** has large complex eigenpairs.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In such cases, BiCGSTAB is likely to stagnate, as confirmed by numerical experiments.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] One may expect that higher-degree minimum residual polynomials may better handle this situation.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] This gives rise to algorithms including BiCGSTAB2[1] and the more general BiCGSTAB(*l*)[2].
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] In BiCGSTAB(*l*), a GMRES(*l*) step follows every *l* BiCG steps.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/biconjugate-gradient-stabilized-method] BiCGSTAB2 is equivalent to BiCGSTAB(*l*) with *l* = 2.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] The **conjugate residual method** is an iterative numeric method used for solving systems of linear equations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] It's a Krylov subspace method very similar to the much more popular conjugate gradient method, with similar construction and convergence properties.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] where **A** is an invertible and Hermitian matrix, and **b** is nonzero.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] The conjugate residual method differs from the closely related conjugate gradient method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] It involves more numerical operations and requires more storage.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] the iteration may be stopped once $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ has been deemed converged.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] The only difference between this and the conjugate gradient method is the calculation of $\alpha _{k}$ and $\beta _{k}$ (plus the optional incremental calculation of $\mathbf {Ap} _{k}$ at the end).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] Note: the above algorithm can be transformed so to make only one symmetric matrix-vector multiplication in each iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] The preconditioner $\mathbf {M} ^{-1}$ must be symmetric positive definite.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/conjugate-residual-method] Note that the residual vector here is different from the residual vector without preconditioning.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In mathematics, the **generalized minimal residual method (GMRES)** is an iterative method for the numerical solution of an indefinite nonsymmetric system of linear equations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The method approximates the solution by the vector in a Krylov subspace with minimal residual.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi iteration is used to find this vector.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The GMRES method was developed by Yousef Saad and Martin H.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] It is a generalization and improvement of the MINRES method due to Paige and Saunders in 1975.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The MINRES method requires the matrix to be symmetric, but has the advantage that it only requires handling of three vectors.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] GMRES is a special case of the DIIS method developed by Peter Pulay in 1980.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] DIIS is applicable to non-linear systems.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Denote the Euclidean norm of any vector **v**by $\|v\|$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Denote the (square) system of linear equations to be solved by $Ax=b.$ The matrix *A* is assumed to be invertible of size *m*-by-*m*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Furthermore, it is assumed that **b** is normalized, i.e., that $\|b\|=1$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] GMRES approximates the exact solution of $Ax=b$ by the vector $x_{n}\in x_{0}+K_{n}$ that minimizes the Euclidean norm of the residual $r_{n}=b-Ax_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The vectors $r_{0},Ar_{0},\ldots A^{n-1}r_{0}$ might be close to linearly dependent, so instead of this basis, the Arnoldi iteration is used to find orthonormal vectors $q_{1},q_{2},\ldots ,q_{n}\,$ which form a basis for $K_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In other words, finding the *n*-th approximation of the solution (i.e., $x_{n}$ ) is reduced to finding the vector $y_{n}$ , which is determined via minimizing the residue as described below.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi process also constructs ${\tilde {H}}_{n}$ , an ( $n+1$ )-by- n upper Hessenberg matrix which satisfies $AQ_{n}=Q_{n+1}{\tilde {H}}_{n}\,$ an equality which is used to simplify the calculation of $y_{n}$ (see § Solving the least squares problem).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Note that, for symmetric matrices, a symmetric tri-diagonal matrix is actually achieved, resulting in the MINRES method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Hence, $x_{n}$ can be found by minimizing the Euclidean norm of the residual $r_{n}={\tilde {H}}_{n}y_{n}-\beta e_{1}.$ This is a linear least squares problem of size *n*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] 4. repeat if the residual is not yet small enough.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] At every iteration, a matrix-vector product $Aq_{n}$ must be computed.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] This costs about $2m^{2}$ floating-point operations for general dense matrices of size m , but the cost can decrease to $O(m)$ for sparse matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In addition to the matrix-vector product, $O(nm)$ floating-point operations must be computed at the *n* -th iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The *n*th iterate minimizes the residual in the Krylov subspace $K_{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Since every subspace is contained in the next subspace, the residual does not increase.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] After *m* iterations, where *m* is the size of the matrix *A*, the Krylov space *K**m* is the whole of **R***m* and hence the GMRES method arrives at the exact solution.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] However, the idea is that after a small number of iterations (relative to *m*), the vector *x**n* is already a good approximation to the exact solution.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Indeed, a theorem of Greenbaum, Pták and Strakoš states that for every nonincreasing sequence *a*1, ..., *a**m*−1, *a**m* = 0, one can find a matrix *A* such that the ‖*r**n*‖ = *a**n* for all *n*, where *r**n* is the residual defined above.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In particular, it is possible to find a matrix for which the residual stays constant for *m* − 1 iterations, and only drops to zero at the last iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] In practice, though, GMRES often performs well.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] This can be proven in specific situations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Roughly speaking, this says that fast convergence occurs when the eigenvalues of *A* are clustered away from the origin and *A* is not too far from normality.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] All these inequalities bound only the residuals instead of the actual error, that is, the distance between the current iterate *x**n* and the exact solution.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Like other iterative methods, GMRES is usually combined with a preconditioning method in order to speed up convergence.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The cost of the iterations grow as O(*n*2), where *n* is the iteration number.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Therefore, the method is sometimes restarted after a number, say *k*, of iterations, with *x**k* as initial guess.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The resulting method is called GMRES(*k*) or Restarted GMRES.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] For non-positive definite matrices, this method may suffer from stagnation in convergence as the restarted subspace is often close to the earlier subspace.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The shortcomings of GMRES and restarted GMRES are addressed by the recycling of Krylov subspace in the GCRO type methods such as GCROT and GCRODR.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Recycling of Krylov subspaces in GMRES can also speed up convergence when sequences of linear systems need to be solved.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The Arnoldi iteration reduces to the Lanczos iteration for symmetric matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The corresponding Krylov subspace method is the minimal residual method (MinRes) of Paige and Saunders.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Unlike the unsymmetric case, the MinRes method is given by a three-term recurrence relation.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] It can be shown that there is no Krylov subspace method for general matrices, which is given by a short recurrence relation and yet minimizes the norms of the residuals, as GMRES does.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Another class of methods builds on the unsymmetric Lanczos iteration, in particular the BiCG method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] These use a three-term recurrence relation, but they do not attain the minimum residual, and hence the residual does not decrease monotonically for these methods.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The third class is formed by methods like CGS and BiCGSTAB.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] These also work with a three-term recurrence relation (hence, without optimality) and they can even terminate prematurely without achieving convergence.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] The idea behind these methods is to choose the generating polynomials of the iteration sequence suitably.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] None of these three classes is the best for all matrices; there are always examples in which one class outperforms the other.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Therefore, multiple solvers are tried in practice to see which one is the best for a given problem.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] One part of the GMRES method is to find the vector $y_{n}$ which minimizes $\left\|{\tilde {H}}_{n}y_{n}-\beta e_{1}\right\|.$ Note that ${\tilde {H}}_{n}$ is an (*n* + 1)-by-*n* matrix, hence it gives an over-constrained linear system of *n*+1 equations for *n* unknowns.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/generalized-minimal-residual-method] Hence, it can be decomposed as ${\tilde {R}}_{n}={\begin{bmatrix}R_{n}\\0\end{bmatrix}},$ where $R_{n}$ is an *n*-by-*n* (thus square) triangular matrix.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] The concept is named after Russian applied mathematician and naval engineer Alexei Krylov, who published a paper about the concept in 1931.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] Krylov subspaces are used in algorithms for finding approximate solutions to high-dimensional linear algebra problems.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] Many linear dynamical system tests in control theory, especially those related to controllability and observability, involve checking the rank of the Krylov subspace.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] These tests are equivalent to finding the span of the Gramians associated with the system/output maps so the uncontrollable and unobservable subspaces are simply the orthogonal complement to the Krylov subspace.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] Modern iterative methods such as Arnoldi iteration can be used for finding one (or a few) eigenvalues of large sparse matrices or solving large systems of linear equations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] They try to avoid matrix-matrix operations, but rather multiply vectors by the matrix and work with the resulting vectors.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] Starting with a vector b , one computes $Ab$ , then one multiplies that vector by A to find $A^{2}b$ and so on.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] All algorithms that work this way are referred to as Krylov subspace methods; they are among the most successful methods currently available in numerical linear algebra.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] These methods can be used in situations where there is an algorithm to compute the matrix-vector multiplication without there being an explicit representation of A , giving rise to matrix-free methods.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] Because the vectors usually soon become almost linearly dependent due to the properties of power iteration, methods relying on Krylov subspace frequently involve some orthogonalization scheme, such as Lanczos iteration for Hermitian matrices or Arnoldi iteration for more general matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/krylov-subspace] The best known Krylov subspace methods are the Conjugate gradient, IDR(s) (Induced dimension reduction), GMRES (generalized minimum residual), BiCGSTAB (biconjugate gradient stabilized), QMR (quasi minimal residual), TFQMR (transpose-free QMR) and MINRES (minimal residual method).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Although computationally efficient in principle, the method as initially formulated was not useful, due to its numerical instability.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] In 1970, Ojalvo and Newman showed how to make the method numerically stable and applied it to the solution of very large engineering structures subjected to dynamic loading.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Soon thereafter their work was followed by Paige, who also provided an error analysis.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] In 1988, Ojalvo produced a more detailed history of this algorithm and an efficient eigenvalue error test.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The Lanczos iteration is prone to numerical instability.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] When executed in non-exact arithmetic, additional measures (as outlined in later sections) should be taken to ensure validity of the results.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] If $\beta _{j}\neq 0$ , then let $v_{j}=w_{j-1}/\beta _{j}$ , else pick as $v_{j}$ an arbitrary vector with Euclidean norm 1 that is orthogonal to all of $v_{1},\dots ,v_{j-1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Let V be the matrix with columns $v_{1},\dots ,v_{m}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] There are in principle four ways to write the iteration procedure.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Paige and other works show that the above order of operations is the most numerically stable.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] In practice the initial vector $v_{1}$ may be taken as another argument of the procedure, with $\beta _{j}=0$ and indicators of numerical imprecision being included as additional loop termination conditions.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Not counting the matrix–vector multiplication, each iteration does $O(n)$ arithmetical operations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The matrix–vector multiplication can be done in $O(dn)$ arithmetical operations where d is the average number of nonzero elements in a row.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The total complexity is thus $O(dmn)$ , or $O(dn^{2})$ if $m=n$ ; the Lanczos algorithm can be very fast for sparse matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Schemes for improving numerical stability are typically judged against this high performance.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The vectors $v_{j}$ are called *Lanczos vectors*.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The vector $w_{j}'$ is not used after $w_{j}$ is computed, and the vector $w_{j}$ is not used after $v_{j+1}$ is computed.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Hence one may use the same storage for all three.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Likewise, if only the tridiagonal matrix T is sought, then the raw iteration does not need $v_{j-1}$ after having computed $w_{j}$ , although some schemes for improving the numerical stability would need it later on.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Sometimes the subsequent Lanczos vectors are recomputed from $v_{1}$ when needed.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Nonetheless, applying the Lanczos algorithm is often a significant step forward in computing the eigendecomposition.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Thus the Lanczos algorithm transforms the eigendecomposition problem for A into the eigendecomposition problem for T .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Some general eigendecomposition algorithms, notably the QR algorithm, are known to converge faster for tridiagonal matrices than for general matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Asymptotic complexity of tridiagonal QR is $O(m^{2})$ just as for the divide-and-conquer algorithm (though the constant factor may be different); since the eigenvectors together have $m^{2}$ elements, this is asymptotically optimal.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Even algorithms whose convergence rates are unaffected by unitary transformations, such as the power method and inverse iteration, may enjoy low-level performance benefits from being applied to the tridiagonal matrix T rather than the original matrix A .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Since T is very sparse with all nonzero elements in highly predictable positions, it permits compact storage with excellent performance vis-à-vis caching.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Likewise, T is a real matrix with all eigenvectors and eigenvalues real, whereas A in general may have complex elements and eigenvectors, so real arithmetic is sufficient for finding the eigenvectors and eigenvalues of T .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The combination of good performance for sparse matrices and the ability to compute several (without computing all) eigenvalues are the main reasons for choosing to use the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Though the eigenproblem is often the motivation for applying the Lanczos algorithm, the operation the algorithm primarily performs is tridiagonalization of a matrix, for which numerically stable Householder transformations have been favoured since the 1950s.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] During the 1960s the Lanczos algorithm was disregarded.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Interest in it was rejuvenated by the Kaniel–Paige convergence theory and the development of methods to prevent numerical instability, but the Lanczos algorithm remains the alternative algorithm that one tries only if Householder is not satisfactory.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] There are several lines of reasoning which lead to the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] It may be desirable to instead keep all the intermediate results and organise the data.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] One piece of information that trivially is available from the vectors $u_{j}$ is a chain of Krylov subspaces.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] this is trivially satisfied by $v_{j}=u_{j}$ as long as $u_{j}$ is linearly independent of $u_{1},\dotsc ,u_{j-1}$ (and in the case that there is such a dependence then one may continue the sequence by picking as $v_{j}$ an arbitrary vector linearly independent of $u_{1},\dotsc ,u_{j-1}$ ).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] A basis containing the $u_{j}$ vectors is however likely to be numerically ill-conditioned, since this sequence of vectors is by design meant to converge to an eigenvector of A .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] To avoid that, one can combine the power iteration with a Gram–Schmidt process, to instead produce an orthonormal basis of these Krylov subspaces.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] This last procedure is the Arnoldi iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The Lanczos algorithm then arises as the simplification one gets from eliminating calculation steps that turn out to be trivial when A is Hermitian—in particular most of the $h_{k,j}$ coefficients turn out to be zero.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] For $k<j-1$ we know that $Av_{k}\in \operatorname {span} (v_{1},\ldots ,v_{j-1})$ , and since $v_{j}$ by construction is orthogonal to this subspace, this inner product must be zero.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] since the latter is real on account of being the norm of a vector.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] More abstractly, if V is the matrix with columns $v_{1},\ldots ,v_{m}$ then the numbers $h_{k,j}$ can be identified as elements of the matrix $H=V^{*}AV$ , and $h_{k,j}=0$ for $k>j+1;$ the matrix H is upper Hessenberg.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] This implies that H is also lower Hessenberg, so it must in fact be tridiagional.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Being Hermitian, its main diagonal is real, and since its first subdiagonal is real by construction, the same is true for its first superdiagonal.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Therefore, H is a real, symmetric matrix—the matrix T of the Lanczos algorithm specification.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] In particular, the largest eigenvalue $\lambda _{\max }$ is the global maximum of r and the smallest eigenvalue $\lambda _{\min }$ is the global minimum of r .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Within a low-dimensional subspace ${\mathcal {L}}$ of $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ it can be feasible to locate the maximum x and minimum y of r .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The question then arises how to choose the subspaces so that these sequences converge at optimal rate.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] From $x_{j}$ , the optimal direction in which to seek larger values of r is that of the gradient $\nabla r(x_{j})$ , and likewise from $y_{j}$ the optimal direction in which to seek smaller values of r is that of the negative gradient $-\nabla r(y_{j})$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] It is not necessary to increase the dimension of ${\mathcal {L}}_{j}$ by 2 on every step if $\{{\mathcal {L}}_{j}\}_{j=1}^{m}$ are taken to be Krylov subspaces, because then $Az\in {\mathcal {L}}_{j+1}$ for all $z\in {\mathcal {L}}_{j},$ thus in particular for both $z=x_{j}$ and $z=y_{j}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Since the j th power method iterate $u_{j}$ belongs to ${\mathcal {L}}_{j},$ it follows that an iteration to produce the $x_{j}$ and $y_{j}$ cannot converge slower than that of the power method, and will achieve more by approximating both eigenvalue extremes.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] For the subproblem of optimising r on some ${\mathcal {L}}_{j}$ , it is convenient to have an orthonormal basis $\{v_{1},\ldots ,v_{j}\}$ for this vector space.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Thus we are again led to the problem of iteratively computing such a basis for the sequence of Krylov subspaces.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] When analysing the dynamics of the algorithm, it is convenient to take the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of A as given, even though they are not explicitly known to the user.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] It is also convenient to fix a notation for the coefficients of the initial Lanczos vector $v_{1}$ with respect to this eigenbasis; let $d_{k}=z_{k}^{*}v_{1}$ for all $k=1,\dotsc ,n$ , so that $\textstyle v_{1}=\sum _{k=1}^{n}d_{k}z_{k}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] A starting vector $v_{1}$ depleted of some eigencomponent will delay convergence to the corresponding eigenvalue, and even though this just comes out as a constant factor in the error bounds, depletion remains undesirable.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] One common technique for avoiding being consistently hit by it is to pick $v_{1}$ by first drawing the elements randomly according to the same normal distribution with mean 0 and then rescale the vector to norm 1 .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] This makes it possible to bound the probability that for example $|d_{1}|<\varepsilon$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The convergence for the Lanczos algorithm is often orders of magnitude faster than that for the power iteration algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The bounds for $\theta _{1}$ come from the above interpretation of eigenvalues as extreme values of the Rayleigh quotient $r(x)$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Since $\lambda _{1}$ is a priori the maximum of r on the whole of $\mathbb {C} ^{n},$ whereas $\theta _{1}$ is merely the maximum on an m -dimensional Krylov subspace, we trivially get $\lambda _{1}\geqslant \theta _{1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Conversely, any point x in that Krylov subspace provides a lower bound $r(x)$ for $\theta _{1}$ , so if a point can be exhibited for which $\lambda _{1}-r(x)$ is small then this provides a tight bound on $\theta _{1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] so any element of it can be expressed as $p(A)v_{1}$ for some polynomial p of degree at most $m-1$ ; the coefficients of that polynomial are simply the coefficients in the linear combination of the vectors $v_{1},Av_{1},A^{2}v_{1},\ldots ,A^{m-1}v_{1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The polynomial we want will turn out to have real coefficients, but for the moment we should allow also for complex coefficients, and we will write $p^{*}$ for the polynomial obtained by complex conjugating all coefficients of p .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] A key difference between numerator and denominator here is that the $k=1$ term vanishes in the numerator, but not in the denominator.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Thus if one can pick p to be large at $\lambda _{1}$ but small at all other eigenvalues, one will get a tight bound on the error $\lambda _{1}-\theta _{1}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Since A has many more eigenvalues than p has coefficients, this may seem a tall order, but one way to meet it is to use Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Writing $c_{k}$ for the degree k Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind (that which satisfies $c_{k}(\cos x)=\cos(kx)$ for all x ), we have a polynomial which stays in the range $[-1,1]$ on the known interval $[-1,1]$ but grows rapidly outside it.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] With some scaling of the argument, we can have it map all eigenvalues except $\lambda _{1}$ into $[-1,1]$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] (i.e., the ratio of the first eigengap to the diameter of the rest of the spectrum) is thus of key importance for the convergence rate here.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The convergence rate is thus controlled chiefly by R , since this bound shrinks by a factor $R^{-2}$ for each extra iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Under that constraint, the case that most favours the power method is that $\lambda _{n}=-\lambda _{2}$ , so consider that.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] which shrinks by a factor of $(1+2\rho )^{-2}$ for each iteration.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The difference thus boils down to that between $1+2\rho$ and $R=1+2\rho +2{\sqrt {\rho ^{2}+\rho }}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] In the $\rho \gg 1$ region, the latter is more like $1+4\rho$ , and performs like the power method would with an eigengap twice as large; a notable improvement.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The more challenging case is however that of $\rho \ll 1,$ in which $R\approx 1+2{\sqrt {\rho }}$ is an even larger improvement on the eigengap; the $\rho \gg 1$ region is where the Lanczos algorithm convergence-wise makes the *smallest* improvement on the power method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Stability means how much the algorithm will be affected (i.e. will it produce the approximate result close to the original one) if there are small numerical errors introduced and accumulated.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Numerical stability is the central criterion for judging the usefulness of implementing an algorithm on a computer with roundoff.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] For the Lanczos algorithm, it can be proved that with *exact arithmetic*, the set of vectors $v_{1},v_{2},\cdots ,v_{m+1}$ constructs an *orthonormal* basis, and the eigenvalues/vectors solved are good approximations to those of the original matrix.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] However, in practice (as the calculations are performed in floating point arithmetic where inaccuracy is inevitable), the orthogonality is quickly lost and in some cases the new vector could even be linearly dependent on the set that is already constructed.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] As a result, some of the eigenvalues of the resultant tridiagonal matrix may not be approximations to the original matrix.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Therefore, the Lanczos algorithm is not very stable.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Users of this algorithm must be able to find and remove those "spurious" eigenvalues.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Recover the orthogonality after the basis is generated.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] After the good and "spurious" eigenvalues are all identified, remove the spurious ones.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Variations on the Lanczos algorithm exist where the vectors involved are tall, narrow matrices instead of vectors and the normalizing constants are small square matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] These are called "block" Lanczos algorithms and can be much faster on computers with large numbers of registers and long memory-fetch times.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Many implementations of the Lanczos algorithm restart after a certain number of iterations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] One of the most influential restarted variations is the implicitly restarted Lanczos method, which is implemented in ARPACK.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] This has led into a number of other restarted variations such as restarted Lanczos bidiagonalization.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Another successful restarted variation is the Thick-Restart Lanczos method, which has been implemented in a software package called TRLan.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Lanczos algorithms are very attractive because the multiplication by $A\,$ is the only large-scale linear operation.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Since weighted-term text retrieval engines implement just this operation, the Lanczos algorithm can be applied efficiently to text documents (see latent semantic indexing).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Eigenvectors are also important for large-scale ranking methods such as the HITS algorithm developed by Jon Kleinberg, or the PageRank algorithm used by Google.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Lanczos algorithms are also used in condensed matter physics as a method for solving Hamiltonians of strongly correlated electron systems, as well as in shell model codes in nuclear physics.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The NAG Library contains several routines for the solution of large scale linear systems and eigenproblems which use the Lanczos algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] ARPACK (FORTRAN 77, also available in MATLAB[1], GNU Octave(eigs), Julia[2], and Python via the SciPy[3] package) focuses on eigenvalue problems, and supports both stored and implicit matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] A Matlab implementation of the Lanczos algorithm (note precision issues) is available as a part of the Gaussian Belief Propagation Matlab Package.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The GraphLab collaborative filtering library incorporates a large scale parallel implementation of the Lanczos algorithm (in C++) for multicore.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] Julia implementations of Lanczos and related Krylov methods can be found in Krylov.jl, KrylovKit.jl, IterativeSolvers.jl, and ArnoldiMethod.jl.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] The PRIMME library also implements a Lanczos-like algorithm.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/lanczos-algorithm] An open source Python package Leymosun implements Lanczos algorithm in the context of Krylov Complexity in pure Python: Its function called *lanczos* will generate Krylov bases and the coefficients.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] The **Minimal Residual Method** or **MINRES** is a Krylov subspace method for the iterative solution of symmetric linear equation systems.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] It was proposed by mathematicians Christopher Conway Paige and Michael Alan Saunders in 1975.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] In contrast to the popular CG method, the MINRES method does not assume that the matrix is positive definite, only the symmetry of the matrix is mandatory.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] The GMRES method is essentially a generalization of MINRES for arbitrary matrices.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] Both minimize the 2-norm of the residual and do the same calculations in exact arithmetic when the matrix is symmetric.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] MINRES is a short-recurrence method with a constant memory requirement, whereas GMRES requires storing the whole Krylov space, so its memory requirement is roughly proportional to the number of iterations.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] On the other hand, GMRES tends to suffer less from loss of orthogonality.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] The MINRES method iteratively calculates an approximate solution of a linear system of equations of the form $Ax=b,$ where $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is a symmetric matrix and $b\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ a vector.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] More precisely, we define the approximate solutions $x_{k}$ through $x_{k}:=\mathrm {argmin} _{x\in V_{k}}\|r(x)\|,$ where $\|\cdot \|$ is the standard Euclidean norm on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] Because of the symmetry of A , unlike in the GMRES method, it is possible to carry out this minimization process recursively, storing only two previous steps (short recurrence).
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] Note: The MINRES method is more complicated than the algebraically equivalent Conjugate Residual method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] The Conjugate Residual (CR) method was therefore produced below as a substitute.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] It differs from MINRES is that in MINRES, the columns of a basis of the Krylov space (denoted below by $p_{k}$ ) can be orthogonalized, whereas in CR their images (below labeled with $s_{k}$ ) can be orthogonalized via the Lanczos recursion.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] There are more efficient and preconditioned variants with fewer AXPYs.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] In the case of positive definite matrices, the convergence rate of the MINRES method can be estimated in a way similar to that of the CG method.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] In contrast to the CG method, however, the estimation does not apply to the errors of the iterates, but to the residual.
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] where $\kappa (A)$ is the condition number of matrix A .
[src:krylov-subspace-methods/minimal-residual-method] Because A is normal, we have $\kappa (A)={\frac {\left|\lambda _{\text{max}}(A)\right|}{\left|\lambda _{\text{min}}(A)\right|}},$ where $\lambda _{\text{max}}(A)$ and $\lambda _{\text{min}}(A)$ are maximal and minimal eigenvalues of A , respectively.
